We say that a family of pairs measures/vector fields $(ho_t,v_t)$ with $v_t\in L^1(ho_t;\mathbb{R}^d)$ and $\int_0^T\|v_t\|_{L^1(ho_t)}dt=\int_0^T\int_{\Omega}|v_t|dho_tdt<+\infty$ solves the continuity equation on (0,T) in the distributional sense if for any bounded and Lipschitz test function $\phi\in C_c^1((0,T	imes\overline{\Omega})$ , we have $$\int_0^T\int_{\Omega}(\partial_t\phi)dho_tdt+\int_0^T\int_{\Omega}
abla\phi\cdot v_t dho_tdt=0$$ We can also define a weak solution of the continuity equation through the following condition: we say that $(ho_t,v_t)$ solves the continuity equation in the weak sense if for any test function $\psi\in C_c^1(\overline{\Omega})$ , the function $t\mapsto\int\psi dho_t$ is absolutely continuous in t and, for a.e. $t$ , we have $$ rac{d}{dt}\int_{\Omega}\psi dho_t=\int_{\Omega}
abla\psi\cdot v_t dho_t$$ Now apparently the two notions of solutions are equivalent, i.e. every weak solution is a distributional solution and every distributional solution is a weak solution. If I consider a distributional solution $(ho_t,v_t)$ and I take the particular "separated" test functions $\phi(t,x)=a(t)\psi(x)$ then I get $$\int_0^T a'(t)\int_{\Omega}\psi(x)dho_t(x)dt=-\int_0^1 a(t)\int_{\Omega}
abla\psi(x)\cdot v_t dho_t(x)dt$$ which means that the distributional derivative of $t\mapsto\int_{\Omega}\psi(x)dho_t(x)$ is $t\mapsto\int_{\Omega}
abla\psi(x)\cdot v_t dho_t(x)$ . But then I don't understand why the actual derivative (not just the distributional derivative) of $t\mapsto\int_{\Omega}\psi(x)dho_t(x)$ is $t\mapsto\int_{\Omega}
abla\psi(x)\cdot v_t dho_t(x)$ .

